snippet.textDisplay: Sundari Komola means "Beautiful Komola" (Sundari means beautiful, Komola is Bangla word for Orange). "Komola" is a very common female name in rural areas of Bangladesh & probably in West Bengal. The song is a common folk song and it has been used for many years in festivals like wedding. It has a deep cultural context. And sorry to say that, Ram Sampath totally failed to represent the essence of the song and in a word, destroyed it. A fusion could have been much better, lost the feelings, lost the heritage, and most importantly, lost the original tone.

snippet.textDisplay: If u don't mind guys, let me tell u a unliking truth, "This song is stolen from Bangladeshi Folk". Now let me tell u, why i've used the term "stolen". Because, original lyrics has been changed, also the accent, rythm and tempo (which consists a song) was not appropiate. Let me clear a thing, Fusion song doesn't allow to change the fundamentals of songs. Yes, you can make the tempo faster but that doesn't mean you can deform it. I'm not Bangladeshi, but I listened lot of Bangladeshi Folk Songs. Lastly, let me a clear a concept, Bangladesh is actually the origin of some types of songs, such as Lalon, Vatiali, Polligeeti, JariSari and some others. Hence, Bangla songs of Bangladesh are much more richer than those of Western Bengal. Anyone can copy but can't mimic, because these songs actually comes from heart and soul and sung by those who have the test and smell of that place. Similarly, it's true if a Bangladeshi tries to sing a Punjabi, Marathi Songs.
